|y=440|scale=546/1820|text=[[Nanxi District, Yibin|'''Nanxi''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=690|y=330|scale=546/1820|text=[[Xuzhou District|'''Xuzhou''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1500|y=660|scale=546/1820|text=[[Jiang'an County|'''Jiang'an<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1240|y=920|scale=546/1820|text=[[Changning County, Sichuan|'''Changning<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=920|y=950|scale=546/1820|text=[[Gao County|'''Gao<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1180|y=1260|scale=546/1820|text=[[Gong County, Sichuan|'''Gong<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=950|y=1450|scale=546/1820|text=[[Junlian County|'''Junlian<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1540|y=1190|scale=546/1820|text=[[Xingwen County|'''Xingwen<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=400|y=650|scale=546/1820|text=[[Pingshan County, Sichuan|'''Pingshan<br>County''']]}}\n</div>\n|-\n! Name\n! [[Hanzi]]\n! [[Hanyu Pinyin]]\n! Population (2010)\n! Area (km\u00b2)\n! Density (/km\u00b2)\n|----------\n|[[Cuiping District]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u7fe0\u5c4f\u533a}}\n|Cu\u00ecp\u00edng Q\u016b\n|836,383\n|1,123\n|745\n|----------\n|[[Nanxi District, Yibin|Nanxi District]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5357\u6eaa\u533a}}\n|N\u00e1nx\u012b Q\u016b\n|335,805\n|704\n|477\n|----------\n|[[Xuzhou District]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u53d9\u5dde\u533a}}\n|X\u00f9zh\u014du Q\u016b\n|813,057\n|3,034\n|268\n|----------\n|[[Jiang'an County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u6c5f\u5b89\u53bf}}\n|Ji\u0101ng'\u0101n Xi\u00e0n\n|399,829\n|910\n|439\n|----------\n|[[Changning County, Sichuan|Changning County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u957f\u5b81\u53bf}}\n|Ch\u00e1ngn\u00edng Xi\u00e0n\n|340,016\n|975\n|349\n|----------\n|[[Gao County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u9ad8\u53bf}}\n|G\u0101o Xi\u00e0n\n|411,118\n|1,323\n|310\n|----------\n|[[Junlian County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u7b60\u8fde\u53bf}}\n|J\u016bnli\u00e1n Xi\u00e0n\n|329,056\n|1,254\n|262\n|----------\n|[[Gong County, Sichuan|Gong County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u73d9\u53bf}}\n|G\u01d2ng Xi\u00e0n\n|379,798\n|1,150\n|330\n|----------\n|[[Xingwen County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5174\u6587\u53bf}}\n|X\u012bngw\u00e9n Xi\u00e0n\n|377,162\n|1,373\n|275\n|----------\n|[[Pingshan County, Sichuan|Pingshan County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5c4f\u5c71\u53bf}}\n|P\u00edngsh\u0101n Xi\u00e0n\n|249,777\n|1,437\n|174\n|}\n\n[[File:Yibin birdview.jpg|thumb|alt=\u7fe0\u5c4f\u5c71\u4fef\u77b0|View of Yibin from Cuiping Mountain]]\n\n==Economy==\nThe city's industry focuses on electronics, food products, and power generation. It also produces paper, silk, and leather products. The surrounding region is rich in agricultural resources, growing rice, barley, oil seeds, sesame, and tea.\n\nThe largest employer in Yibin is [[Wuliangye Yibin|Wuliangye]], a company best known for Wuliangye, a brand of [[sorghum]]-based [[distilled beverage|distilled spirits]] known as [[baijiu]]. The Wuliangye Group grew from a small company employing just 300 people in 1977 into a large company employing over 20,000 on a seven square kilometer plant.  According to an August 2005 article in a securities weekly, the Wuliangye Group is 72% state owned and provides 70% of the revenues of Yibin City, a major regional center at the head of the Yangtze in southeastern Sichuan. In 2004 6,225 retired military worked for the company, out of a total work force of over 20,000. One third of top management positions are held by retired members of the military.<ref>[http://www.chinamil.com.cn/gb/defence/2004/07/29/20040729017053.html \"An Army of Production Out of Uniform: Retired Soldiers at Wuliangye\", PLA Daily July 29, 2004]</ref> Unsuccessful efforts to diversify its business, poor transparency and a murky ownership pictures are among the company's problems today.<ref>[http://cn.biz.yahoo.com/050822/133/c43m.html \"Stockholder Interests Poorly Represented, This is How Profits Slip Away,\" ''Bond Market Weekly'', August 22, 2005]</ref>  However, liquor is not the sole product of the WuLiangye Group. It also provides the specialized high-tech anti-counterfeit packaging and printing business and engineering services. Wuliangye now contributes about 60% of Yibin's GDP.\n\n==Transportation==\nThe region's natural waterways provide transportation links with the surrounding area, and Yibin is also connected to [[Chongqing]] and [[Chengdu]] by rail and express highway. Yibin's proximity to the Yunnan and Guizhou borders also means that transportation to the provinces is available by rail and by bus.\n\nYibin has three [[Yangtze River bridges and tunnels#From Shanghai to Yibin: Chang Jiang|bridges over the ''Chang Jiang'' section of the Yangtze]] and ten [[Yangtze River bridges and tunnels#From Yibin to Yushu: The Jinsha|bridges over the Jinsha]].\n\n[[Yibin Airport]] offers flights to [[Beijing]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Guiyang]], [[Hangzhou]], [[Kunming]], [[Lhasa]], [[Sanya]], [[Shanghai]],  [[Shenzhen]], [[Xi'an]], and [[Yichang]].\n\n==Tourism==\nThere are several hot springs near Yibin, plus many other tourist attractions. Such attractions include the Bamboo Sea in Changning County and the Xingwen Stone Forest. Cuiping mountain in the centre of the city provides wonderful views of Yibin. Yibin is also the confluence of the [[Min River (Sichuan)|Min]] and [[Jinsha River]]s, which together form the ''Chang Jiang'' as the [[Yangtze River]] is known in Chinese from Yibin to Shanghai.\n\nThe most significant scenic resource is Cuiping Mountain Park (Cuipingshan gongyuan,\u7fe0\u5c4f\u5c71\u516c\u56ed), which stretches for hundreds of kilometers.\n\n==Yibin in Literature==\n* ''Dragonfly Eyes'' by [[Cao Wenxuan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://africa.chinadaily.com.cn/life/2016-07/27/content_26237481.htm |title=Readers relishing Cao Wenxuan's latest novel |date=27 July 2016 |author=Mei Jia |website=[[China Daily]] |access-date=2018-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite EB9 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Su-chow |volume=22 |ref={{harvid|''EB''|1887}} |page=617 }}.\n* {{cite EB1911 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Su-chow |volume=26 |ref={{harvid|''EB''|1911}} |page=7 }}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yibin.gov.cn/ Official city website]\n* [http://www.644000.com/home.html Unofficial city briefing of Yibin]\n* [http://www.bashu.net/geography/yibin/e_index.htm Yibin City on bashu.net]\n* [http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/en_travel/2003-09/24/content_35574.htm Yibin on chinaculture.org]\n\n{{Sichuan}}\n{{Major cities along the Yangtze River}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Yibin| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Yangtze River]]\n[[Category:Prefecture-level divisions of Sichuan]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Ipin|the South Korea identification number|I-PIN||Yibin County}}\n{{redirect|Xuzhou, Sichuan|the town in northeastern Sichuan|Xuzhou Town}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox Settlement for additional fields that may be available-->\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                   = {{raise|0.2em|Yibin}}\n|official_name          = \n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5b9c\u5bbe\u5e02}}}}}}\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        =[[Prefecture-level city]]\n|total_type             = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              =\n|image_caption          = The skyline of Yibin\n|image_flag             =\n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             =\n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           =\n|shield_size            =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_type      =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map              = Sichuan subdivisions - Yibin.svg\n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = Location of Yibin City (jurisdiction) in Sichuan\n|pushpin_map            = China\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in China\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin