pe:adm2nd_region:CN-51_source:Gaode|format=dms|display=it}}\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = [[Postal code of China|Postal code]]\n|postal_code            = 644000\n|area_code              = 0831\n|iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-SC-15]]\n|blank_name             =<!-- [[GDP]] -->\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =<!-- GDP per capita -->\n|blank1_info            =\n|blank2_name            = [[Licence plates of the People's Republic of China|Licence Plate]] Prefix\n|blank2_info            = {{lang|zh-cn|\u5dddQ}}\n|website                = {{URL|yibin.gov.cn}}\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n'''Yibin''' ({{zh|s=\u5b9c\u5bbe |t=\u5b9c\u8cd3 |p=Y\u00edb\u012bn |w=I-pin|region=CN-SC-15}}; [[Sichuanese Pinyin]]: nyi<sup>2</sup>bin<sup>1</sup>; [[Sichuanese Mandarin|Sichuanese pronunciation]]: {{IPA-xx|\u0272i\u02e8\u02e9pin\u02e5|}}) is a [[prefecture-level city]] in the southeastern part of [[Sichuan]] province, China, located at the junction of the [[Min River (Sichuan)|Min]] and [[Yangtze River]]s. Its population was 4,471,840 inhabitants according to the 2010 census of whom 836,340 lived in the built-up area made of Cuiping District.\n\n==History==\nHuman habitation of Yibin dates back at least 4,000 years. Yibin was established as a county in the [[Han dynasty]] (206 BC \u2212 AD 220). Under the [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] and [[Qing dynasty|Qing]], the town and its hinterland was known as '''Xuzhou''' [[fu (administrative subdivision)|Commandery]] {{nowrap|(<small>[[traditional characters|t]]</small> {{lang|zh|{{linktext|\u6558\u5dde|\u5e9c}}}},}} {{nowrap|<small>[[simplified characters|s]]</small> {{lang|zh|{{linktext|\u53d9\u5dde|\u5e9c}}}},}} <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>{{nbsp}}''X\u00f9zh\u014duf\u01d4''), which was variously romanized as '''Suifu''', '''Suifoo''',{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} and '''Suchow'''.{{sfnp|''EB''|1887}} Its population around 1907 was estimated at 50,000.{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}}\n\n==Geography and climate==\n[[File:Yibin Yangtze Begins Here.jpg|thumb|left|The Yangtze at the confluence of the Min and [[Jinsha River|Jinsha]] Rivers.  Below Yibin, the Yangtze is known in Chinese as ''Chang Jiang'' or the \"Long River\".  Above Yibin, the Yangtze is known as the Jinsha or Gold Sands River.]]\n\nYibin is located in the southeast portion of Sichuan at the southern end of the [[Sichuan Basin]], bordering [[Zhaotong]] ([[Yunnan]]) to the south, [[Luzhou]] to the east, [[Liangshan Yi Autonomous Prefecture]] and [[Leshan]] to the west, and [[Zigong]] to the north, and has a total area is {{convert|13283|sqkm|0}}. The city ranges in latitude from 27\u00b0 50'\u221229\u00b0 16' N, and in longitude from 103\u00b0 36'\u2212105\u00b0 20' E, stretching {{convert|153|km|abbr=on}} east-west and {{convert|150|km|abbr=on}} north-south.\n\nThe city is located at the confluence of the Min and Yangtze Rivers.  Above Yibin, the Yangtze is also known as the [[Jinsha River]].  Below Yibin, the Yangtze is known in Chinese as the ''Chang Jiang'' or \"Long River.\"\n\nAs with the rest of the Sichuan Basin, Yibin has a [[monsoon]]-influenced [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Cwa'') with high humidity year-round; winters are short and mild while summers long, hot, and humid. The monthly 24-hour average temperature ranges from {{convert|7.9|\u00b0C|1}} in January to {{convert|26.9|\u00b0C|1}} in July and August; the annual mean is {{convert|18.03|\u00b0C|1}}. Despite its location in the Yangtze River valley, it is still {{convert|1.5|to|2.0|C-change|F-change}} cooler than [[Chongqing]], located further downstream, in its warmest months. Frost is uncommon and the frost-free period lasts 347 days.<ref name=\"Weather China\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.com.cn/cityintro/101271101.shtml? |script-title=zh:\u5b9c\u5bbe - \u6c14\u8c61\u6570\u636e -\u4e2d\u56fd\u5929\u6c14\u7f51|website=Weather China}}</ref> Rainfall is common year-round but is the greatest in July and August, with very little of it in the cooler months. With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 10% in December and January to 42% in August, the city receives only 1,018 hours of bright sunshine annually; Yibin has one of the lowest annual sunshine totals nationally, lower than even nearby Chengdu and Chongqing. Spring (March\u2013April) tends to be sunnier and warmer in the day than autumn (October\u2013November).\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|metric first=y\n|single line=y \n|collapsed = Y\n|location = Yibin (1981\u22122010)\n|Jan high C = 10.5\n|Feb high C = 13.1\n|Mar high C = 17.8\n|Apr high C = 23.4\n|May high C = 27.4\n|Jun high C = 29.0\n|Jul high C = 31.5\n|Aug high C = 31.3\n|Sep high C = 27.0\n|Oct high C = 21.6\n|Nov high C = 17.3\n|Dec high C = 11.8\n|Jan mean C = 7.9\n|Feb mean C = 9.9\n|Mar mean C = 13.8\n|Apr mean C = 18.8\n|May mean C = 22.7\n|Jun mean C = 24.7\n|Jul mean C = 26.9\n|Aug mean C = 26.6\n|Sep mean C = 23.1\n|Oct mean C = 18.4\n|Nov mean C = 14.2\n|Dec mean C = 9.3\n|year mean C = \n|Jan low C = 6.0\n|Feb low C = 7.8\n|Mar low C = 11.1\n|Apr low C = 15.5\n|May low C = 19.3\n|Jun low C = 21.7\n|Jul low C = 23.7\n|Aug low C = 23.4\n|Sep low C = 20.5\n|Oct low C = 16.4\n|Nov low C = 12.3\n|Dec low C = 7.5\n|Jan record high C = 19.6 |Jan record low C = -1.0\n|Feb record high C = 25.2 |Feb record low C = 0.4\n|Mar record high C = 32.0 |Mar record low C = 1.1\n|Apr record high C = 34.5 |Apr record low C = 7.1\n|May record high C = 37.1 |May record low C = 10.3\n|Jun record high C = 37.2 |Jun record low C = 16.0\n|Jul record high C = 38.0 |Jul record low C = 18.5\n|Aug record high C = 40.0 |Aug record low C = 17.8\n|Sep record high C = 38.3 |Sep record low C = 14.5\n|Oct record high C = 31.0 |Oct record low C = 5.9\n|Nov record high C = 26.4 |Nov record low C = 3.4\n|Dec record high C = 19.5 |Dec record low C = -1.4\n|year high C=  |year low C= \n|year high F = |year low F =\n|precipitation colo