{"title_page": "Heather the Leather", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2013}}\n'''Heather the Leather''' (1960 \u2013 1 June 2010) was a 50-year-old scaleless (also known as leather) [[carp]], described as \"Britain's most famous fish\".<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/anglers-mourning-the-end-of-the-line-for-heather-the-leather-5k30399mxjb |title=Anglers mourn end of the line for 'Heather the Leather'|newspaper=The Times|date=8 June 2010|page=12}}</ref> Heather was an old and large carp, weighing {{convert|52|lb|kg}} and despite incorrect allegations in the press of being caught over 1000 times, she was likely caught by fishermen approximately 75 times.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} A full list of the captures was recorded by Yateley anglers on the that-aint-no-bream website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forum.that-aint-no-bream.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=2061 |title=Heather captures |website=that-aint-no-bream.co.uk |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082727/http://forum.that-aint-no-bream.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=2061 |archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=Internet Forum, self-published|date=September 2015}} She was deemed by many carp anglers, both in the UK and across Europe, as the ultimate fish to catch given her age, history and catch difficulty.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nAt the time of her death in June 2010 she was around 50 years old and worth \u00a330,000.<ref name=\"times\"/> Heather was discovered dead at the edge of a lake at [[Yateley Complex]] on 1 June 2010, and is thought to have died of old age.<ref name=\"times\"/> The fish was buried by anglers near the lake with a [[headstone]] and memorial rosebush.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Individual fish]]\n[[Category:Recreational fishing in England]]\n[[Category:2010 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Fish of Europe]]\n[[Category:1960 animal births]]\n[[Category:Individual animals in England]]\n[[Category:2010 in England]]\n[[Category:Individual wild animals]]\n\n{{England-stub}}\n{{Cyprinidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2013}}\n'''Heather the Leather''' (1960 \u2013 1 June 2010) was a 50-year-old scaleless (also known as leather) [[carp]], described as \"Britain's most famous fish\".<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news|title=Anglers mourn end of the line for 'Heather the Leather'|newspaper=The Times|date=8 June 2010|page=12}}</ref> Heather was an old and large carp, weighing {{convert|52|lb|kg}} and despite incorrect allegations in the press of being caught over 1000 times, she was likely caught by fishermen approximately 75 times.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} A full list of the captures was recorded by Yateley anglers on the that-aint-no-bream website.<ref>''[http://forum.that-aint-no-bream.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=2061 Heather Captures] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082727/http://forum.that-aint-no-bream.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=2061 |date=2016-03-04 }}'', that-aint-no-bream.co.uk</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=Internet Forum, self-published|date=September 2015}} She was deemed by many carp anglers, both in the UK and across Europe, as the ultimate fish to catch given her age, history and catch difficulty.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nAt the time of her death in June 2010 she was around 50 years old and worth \u00a330,000.<ref name=\"times\"/> Heather was discovered dead at the edge of a lake at [[Yateley Complex]] on 1 June 2010, and is thought to have died of old age.<ref name=\"times\"/> The fish was buried by anglers near the lake with a [[headstone]] and memorial rosebush.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Individual fish]]\n[[Category:Recreational fishing in England]]\n[[Category:2010 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Fish of Europe]]\n[[Category:1960 animal births]]\n[[Category:Individual animals in England]]\n[[Category:2010 in England]]\n[[Category:Individual wild animals]]\n\n{{England-stub}}\n{{Cyprinidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dawkeye", "label": "safe", "comment": "fmt/update references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heather_the_Leather"}
{"title_page": "Butterflies (Michael Jackson song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2002 single by Michael Jackson}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Butterflies\n| cover      = Butterflies02.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Michael Jackson]]\n| album      = [[Invincible (Michael Jackson album)|Invincible]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2002|2|8|mf=y}}\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[12-inch single|12\" single]]\n| recorded   = 2001\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = <!-- Sourced in Composition section. Do not add unsourced genres -->\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n*[[neo soul]]\n*[[lo-fi]]\n| length     = 4:40\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Andre Harris]], [[Marsha Ambrosius]], [[Michael Jackson]]\n| producer   = Michael Jackson, Andre Harris\n| prev_title = [[Cry (Michael Jackson song)|Cry]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[One More Chance (Michael Jackson song)|One More Chance]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|csvNBRZfFpo|\"Butterflies (Audio)\"}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Michael Jackson's Butterflies.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Butterflies'''\" is a song by American singer, songwriter, and dancer [[Michael Jackson]]. It was written and composed by [[Andre Harris]] and [[Marsha Ambrosius]], and produced by Jackson and Harris. The track appears on Jackson's tenth studio album, ''[[Invincible (Michael Jackson album)|Invincible]]'' (2001), and is Jackson's final single from a studio album. The song also appeared in \"[[The Ultimate Collection (Michael Jackson album)|The Ultimate Collection]]\" (2004). \"Butterflies\" is a [[tempo|midtempo]] ballad. The single received generally positive reviews from music critics; some music reviewers described the song as being one of the best songs on ''Invincible'' while others felt that it was a \"decent track\".\n\nThe song was only released in the United States to radio airplay. It peaked at number fourteen on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and also charting at number two and thirty-six, respectively, on alternative ''Billboard'' charts in 2001 and 2002. There was no music video released for the song.\n\n==Background and development==\n\"Butterflies\" was recorded by [[Michael Jackson]] in 2001 for his tenth studio album, ''Invincible'', which was released the same year.<ref name=\"linernotes\">''Invincible'' liner notes [[Epic Records]] (2001)</ref> The song was written by Andre Harris and Marsha Ambrosius, who is one half of the London bred [[neo-soul]] act Floetry,<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> and was produced by Jackson and Harris.<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> Jackson first met Ambrosius and Natalie Stewart, who is also a member of [[Floetry]], through John McClain, who is [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]]'s senior urban executive and Jackson's manager.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> Stewart said she was surprised that Jackson invited her and Ambrosius to a studio and asked for their input on the recording of the track.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> She recalled in an interview with [[LAUNCH Media|''LAUNCH'' magazine]], \"It was incredible because he asked, he continually asked, 'Marsh, what's the next harmony? Girls, does this sound right? What do you think? Is this what you were looking for? He was so open\".<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/>\n\nWhen Ambrosius first met Jackson, it took a few minutes to calm down.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> She recalled to the same publication Stewart was interviewed by, \"To begin with, I was kinda shook. Because you don't realize how you're going to feel until you're put in that situation. I had the tears in my eyes and got kinda nervous. But as I got into it, I realized it was work, it was a job. I had to vocally conduct a legend.\"<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> Harris commented on the single, \"He's showing you, I'm still the Michael Jackson that did '[[Billie Jean]]' and '[[Rock with You (Michael Jackson song)|Rock With You]]' because 'Butterflies' really falls along those lines.\"<ref name=\"theatlanitcjournal\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F0F007E21514E96&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=With a new album, a popular single, and in demand as a hot commodity on television, Michael Jackson proves he's still.... A fan favorite |publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]] |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |date=2002-01-09 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\nUnlike the previous single released from ''Invincible'', a music video was not made to promote the song.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/134224701.html?dids=134224701:134224701&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+09%2C+2002&author=CHUCK+PHILIPS&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Power%2C+Money+Behind+Jackson's+Attack+on+Sony%2C+Insiders+Say%3B+Music%3A+Some+in+the+industry+question+the+pop+singer's+motives+in+going+after+his+longtime+record+company.&pqatl=google |title=Power, Money Behind Jackson's Attack on Sony, Insiders Say; Music: Some in the industry question the pop singer's motives in going after his longtime record company. |first=Chuck |last=Phillips |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=2002-07-09 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Butterflies\" is a [[tempo|midtempo]] love ballad song with groove musical influences.<ref name=\"buffalonews\"/><ref name=\"n.s.t\"/><ref name=\"nyt\"/> Vaughn Watson of the ''[[Providence Journal]]'' noted that the track is a \"velvety old-school soul ballad\" with \"elegiac horn riffs\" and \"simple '70s-style [[David Ruffin]] soul.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Spears and Jackson: Mostly stuck in old grooves |first=Vaughn |last=Watson |publisher=[[A. H. Belo]] |work=[[Providence Journal]] |date=2001-11-11}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]], a writer for [[AllMusic]] noted that \"Butterflies\" had \"[[Burt Bacharach|Bacharach]]-styled horns.\"<ref name=\"allmusicreview\"/> Lonell Broadnax, Jr., a contributing writer to the Daily Helmsman Online felt that \"Butterflies\" is a soulful song which takes Jackson back to his \"rhythm and blues roots\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.www.dailyhelmsman.com/media/storage/paper875/news/2001/10/31/ArtsEntertainment/In.Fans.Eyes.Jackson.Still.invincible-1752586.shtml |title=In fans' eyes, Jackson still 'Invincible' |publisher=Daily Helmsman Online |date=2010-10-31 |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006045016/http://media.www.dailyhelmsman.com/media/storage/paper875/news/2001/10/31/ArtsEntertainment/In.Fans.Eyes.Jackson.Still.invincible-1752586.shtml |archivedate=2008-10-06 }}</ref> Ben Rayer of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' felt that the song had a \"oozy slow jam\".<ref name=\"tornontostar\"/>  \"Butterflies\" is written in the [[time signature]] of common time.<ref name=\"sheet\"/> Throughout the song Jackson's [[vocal range]] spans from E{{music|flat}}3 to E{{music|flat}}5.<ref name=\"sheet\"/> The track is played in the [[key (music)|key]] of A{{music|flat}} major.<ref name=\"sheet\">{{cite web |url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0041745|title=Butterflies \u2013 Michael Jackson Digital Sheet Music (Digital Download)|work=MusicNotes.com|publisher=[[Alfred Publishing|Alfred Publishing Co. Inc]]|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref> \"Butterflies\" has a moderately slowly tempo and its metronome is ninety-two [[beats per minute]].<ref name=\"sheet\"/>\n\n==Critical response==\nThe track received generally positive reviews from music critics. Ken Barnes of ''[[USA Today]]'' described the song as being a \"hopelessly sappy ballad oozing with fuzzy sentiments. I'd say it's more like caterpillars.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/96970620.html?dids=96970620:96970620&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+27%2C+2001&author=Ken+Barnes&pub=USA+TODAY&desc=Singling+out+the+year's+high%2C+low+notes&pqatl=google |first=Ken |last=Barnes |title=Singling out the year's high, low notes |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=Gannett Co. Inc |date=2001-12-21 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Frank Kogan of ''[[The Village Voice]]'', citing the lyrics, \"I would give you anything baby, just make my dreams come true/Oh baby you give me butterflies\" wrote \"so, would he give her, like, caterpillars in exchange? birds?\" and added that what grabs his attention about a song like \"Butterflies\" is not the \"melody but the weirdly ringing wrench-against-faucet clang on the backbeat.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2001-11-27/music/the-man-in-the-distance/ |title=The Man in the Distance |first=Frank |last=Kogan |work=[[The Village Voice]] |publisher=[[Village Voice Media]] |date=2001-11-27 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Christie Leo of the ''[[New Straits Times]]'' gave the track a more positive review, calling the song a \"luxuriant\" ballad.<ref name=\"n.s.t\">{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-82629981.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104020259/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-82629981.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-11-04 |title=Article: Compelling Tori |first=Christie |last=Leo |publisher=[[Media Prima]] |work=[[New Straits Times]] |date=2001-12-02 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Pop music critic [[Robert Hilburn]], writing for the ''Los Angeles Times'', described \"Butterflies\", and another song from ''Invincible'' (\"[[Speechless (Michael Jackson song)|Speechless]]\"), as being \"as woefully generic as their titles\".<ref name=\"Michael Jackson's 'Invincible'\">{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-archive-invincible-review-oct28,0,1825017.story|title=Michael Jackson's 'Invincible' |last=Hilburn |first=Robert |date=2001-10-28 |publisher=Tribune Company |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> A journalist of the same publication felt that track was about romantic \"jitters\".<ref name=\"Michael Jackson's 'Invincible2'\">{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/86729836.html?dids=86729836:86729836&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+28%2C+2001&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Pop+Music%3B+Record+Rack%3B+All+the+King's+Men+Can't+Help&pqatl=google |title=Pop Music; Record Rack; All the King's Men Can't Help|date=2001-10-28 |publisher=Tribune Company |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\nDarryl Frierson of ''University Wire'' felt that songs like \"Butterflies\" can set the \"mood for any romantic interlude\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-47950587.html |title=Article: CD REVIEW: New album proves Michael Jackson is 'invincible' |first=Darryl |last=Frierson |publisher=University Wire |date=2001-11-05 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Joel Rubinoff of ''The Record'' said that \"Butterflies\" was one of the \"only good songs\" from ''Invincible'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/432937431.html?dids=432937431:432937431&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+03%2C+2001&author=Joel+Rubinoff&pub=The+Record&desc=What+has+Michael+Jackson+done+to+deserve+this%3F&pqatl=google |title=What has Michael Jackson done to deserve this? |first=Joel |last=Rubinoff |publisher=The Record |date=2001-11-03 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> while a writer for ''[[The Atlanta Journal]]'' cited the song as being a \"decent track\".<ref>{{cite news |title=He's been 'Dangerous', 'Bad,' now -- ho-hum -- 'Invincible'  |publisher=Cox Enterprises |work=[[The Atlanta Journal]] |date=2001-10-31}}</ref>\n\nA writer for ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' viewed \"Butterflies\" as being \"laid-back\".<ref name=\"theatlanitcjournal\"/> Mark Anthony Neal of ''[[PopMatters]]'' wrote in his music review for Jackson's 2002 album, entitled ''Love Songs'', that in song's such as \"Butterflies\", it shows the \"essence\" of Jackson's \"genius has been in the boy's uncanny ability to perform, even the mundane, outside of the box.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/j/jacksonmichael-love.shtml |title=Michael Jackson: Love Songs  |first=Mark Anthony |last=Neal |work=[[PopMatters]] |publisher=PopMatters Media, Inc |date=2002-01-15 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Elliot Sylvester of ''[[The Independent]]'' felt that ballads on ''Invincible'' such as \"Speechless and \"Butterflies\" are \"almost to a formulaic fault.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Invincible shows that Jackson is not |first=Elliot |last=Sylvester |publisher=[[Alexander Lebedev]] |work=[[The Independent]] |date=2002-01-14}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' rock music critic Greg Kot said that Jackson is not \"convincing as the vulnerable ladies' man on drippy ballads\" such as \"Butterflies\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/86764359.html?dids=86764359:86764359&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+29%2C+2001&author=Greg+Kot%2C+Tribune+rock+critic&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Neither+off-the-wall+nor+off-the-charts+%3B+Michael+Jackson's+%60Invincible'+a+big+disappointment&pqatl=google |title=Neither off-the-wall nor off-the-charts ; Michael Jackson's `Invincible' a big disappointment |first=Greg |last=Kot |work=Chicago Tribune |publisher=Tribune Company |date=2001-10-29 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Stephen Thomas Erlewine, a writer for Allmusic, commented that ''Invincible'' was \"highlighted\" by \"lovely ballads\" such as \"Break of Dawn\" and \"Butterflies\".<ref name=\"allmusicreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=A0dq5g4hptv8z |title=allmusic ((( Invincible &gt; Overview ))) |first=Stephen Thomas |last=Erlewine |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012150712/http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=A0dq5g4hptv8z |archivedate=October 12, 2007 }}</ref> David Browne of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote in his review for ''Invincible'' that, \"The ballads are a squishy bunch with glaringly banal lyrics, pleasantries like 'Butterflies' and 'Break of Dawn' that could emanate from just about\" anyone.<ref name=\"e.w.review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,253595,00.html |title=Invincible (2001) |author=David Browne |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=Time Warner Inc |date=2001-11-09 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> A journalist for ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' called the track \"gorgeous\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF9D51191826730&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=King of Pop is back, with slick, soulless 'Invincible' |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=2001-11-04 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> and Bomani Jones of [[Salon.com]] called \"Butterflies\" a \"sparkling\" track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/music/feature/2002/06/26/jacko |title=Who's bad? |work=[[Salon.com]] |publisher=Salon Media Group, Inc |first=Bomani |last=Jones |date=2002-06-26 |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624085257/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/music/feature/2002/06/26/jacko |archivedate=2010-06-24 }}</ref> Ben Rayer of the ''Toronto Star'' wrote that Jackson \"fares best\" on \"Butterflies\".<ref name=\"tornontostar\">{{cite news |title=Invincible incredibly insipid ; New album is not the come-back Jackson has been hoping for |first=Ben |last=Rayner |publisher=[[Torstar]] |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2001-10-31}}</ref>\n\nCatherine Halaby of the ''[[Yale Daily News]]'' said that songs on the album like \"Heaven Can Wait\", \"Butterflies\", and \"You Are My Life\" \"fulfill the quota for sugary ballads\".<ref name=\"yalesnews\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/scene/music/2001/11/02/jacko-exposes-mortality-in-invincible/ |title=Jacko exposes mortality in Invincible |first=Catherine |last=Halaby |publisher=The Yale Daily News Publishing Company |work=[[Yale Daily News]] |date=2001-11-02 |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916102527/http://www.yaledailynews.com/news/2001/nov/02/jacko-exposes-mortality-in-invincible/ |archivedate=2012-09-16 }}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]], writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', said that tracks on ''Invincible'' like \"Butterflies\"' and \"Don't Walk Away\" are \"melting love ballads\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/28/arts/music-to-regain-glory-the-new-michael-imitates-the-old.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 |first=Jon |last=Pareles |authorlink=Jon Pareles|title=Music; To Regain Glory, The New Michael Imitates the Old (Page 2) |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[New York Times Company]] |date=2001-10-28 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Pareles noted in his review for the album that songs on it are recurring themes present on Jackson's albums, such as love ballads, as well as tracks pertaining to making the world a better place.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Tim Perzyk of the ''[[Duke Chronicle]]'' wrote, \"By the time 'Butterflies' spins on track seven, it's unclear why Michael didn't record a collaborative boxed set with [[Mariah Carey]], whose '[[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]],' '[[Breakdown (Mariah Carey song)|Breakdown]]' and '[[Butterfly (Mariah Carey song)|Butterfly]]' would fit quite nicely\" into Jackson's ''Invincible'' album.<ref name=\"Jackson sucks\">{{cite web |url=http://dukechronicle.com/article/jackson-sucks|title=Jackson sucks |last=Perzyk |first=Tim |date=2001-11-02 |publisher=DSPC |work=[[Duke Chronicle]] |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Pop music critic Craid Seymour of the ''[[Buffalo News]]'' wrote that \"another winning tune\" on the album is the \"dreamy 'Butterflies,' which flows along at a groovy midtempo pace.\"<ref name=\"buffalonews\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF6A5BCB107E9D8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=SAME OLD JACKO |first=Craig |last=Seymour |publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]] |work=[[Buffalo News]] |date=2001-10-26 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Kevin C. Johnson of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' described \"Butterflies\" as being about the \"feeling that special someone gives him.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF8ACBD77152066&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=JACKSON'S \"INVINCIBLE\" ISN'T \"BAD, \"JUST \"OLD\" |first=Kevin C. |last=Johnson |publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]] |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |date=2001-11-02 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Music critics writing for the ''[[South Florida Sun Sentinel]]'' said that the track shows the \"shy, loving, gentle side\" of Jackson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/access/93070637.html?dids=93070637:93070637&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+30%2C+2001&author=Dwight+Roache+Stoneman+Douglas+High+By+Megan+Leap+Spanish+River+High+By+Greg+Overzat+Stoneman+Douglas+High&pub=South+Florida+Sun+-+Sentinel&desc=THE+JACKSON+LEGEND&pqatl=google |title=THE JACKSON LEGEND |publisher=Tribune Company |work=[[South Florida Sun Sentinel]] |date=2001-11-30 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Butterflies\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in early November 2001, at number sixty.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\">{{cite web |url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/michael-jackson/news/artist-name-michael-jackson-id-1013025-songwriter-gets-the-butterflies--12063973 |title=Songwriter Gets The 'Butterflies' |first=Billy |last=Johnson Jr. |work=Yahoo Music |publisher=Yahoo Inc |date=2001-11-15 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> The single eventually peaked at number fourteen on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 the week ending January 26, 2002. The track also charted within the top ten, peaking at number two, on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart on January 26, 2002;<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/> the song was held from the top position from [[Ja Rule]] and [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]]'s \"[[Always on Time]]\" 2001 single.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2002-01-26/r-b-hip-hop-songs |title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs: Week of January 26, 2002 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]] |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> In 2002, \"Butterflies\" also peaked at number thirty-six on the ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Charts|Top 40 Mainstream]] chart.<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/> The track, which was released as a promotional single internationally, did not chart on any music charts outside of the United States.<ref name=\"lescharts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Butterflies&cat=s |title=MICHAEL JACKSON - BUTTERFLIES (CHANSON) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> The song was Jackson's last hit single in the United States in the final years of his career.\n\n==Track listings==\n;Promo CD single (Epic ESK 54863)<ref name=\"lescharts\"/>\n# \"Butterflies\" (album version) \u2013 4:40\n\n;Michael Jackson - Butterflies (Track Masters Remix)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Michael-Jackson-Butterflies-Track-Masters-Remix/release/459620 |title=Michael Jackson - Butterflies (Track Masters Remix) |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=2001-05-10}}</ref>\n*A1. \"Butterflies\" (Master Mix) (featuring Eve) \u2013 3:47\n*A2. \"Butterflies\" (Michael a cappella) \u2013 2:13\n*B1. \"Butterflies\" (Eve a cappella) (featuring Eve) \u2013 3:47\n*B2. \"Butterflies\" (Master Mix Instrumental) \u2013 3:47\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n* Written and composed by Andre Harris, Michael Jackson and Marsha Ambrosius\n* Produced by Michael Jackson and Andre Harris\n* [[Lead vocalist|Lead vocal]] by Michael Jackson\n* Background vocals by Michael Jackson and Marsha Ambrosius\n* All musical instruments performed by Andre Harris\n* [[French horn|Horns]] by Norman Jeff Bradshaw and Matt Cappy\n* Recorded by Andre Harris and Bruce Swedien\n* Assistant engineering by Vidal Davis\n* Mixed by Bruce Rammkisoon\n\nSource:<ref>Liner notes of ''Invincible'' (2001).</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2002)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]]<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Charts|Top 40 Mainstream]]<ref name=\"billboard singles\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r553140|pure_url=yes}} |title=allmusic ((( Invincible > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles ))) |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref>\n|align=center|36\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2002)\n!Position\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billboardtop100of.com/2002-2/|title=Billboard Top 100 \u2013 2002|website=Billboardtop100of.com|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|64\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.discogs.com/Michael-Jackson-Butterflies/release/1994507 \"Butterflies\"] at [[Discogs]]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|michael-jackson|butterflies}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Michael Jackson songs}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butterflies (Michael Jackson Song)}}\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:2002 singles]]\n[[Category:Michael Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n[[Category:Contemporary R&B ballads]]\n[[Category:Soul ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Andre Harris]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Marsha Ambrosius]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Michael Jackson]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2002 single by Michael Jackson}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Butterflies\n| cover      = Butterflies02.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Michael Jackson]]\n| album      = [[Invincible (Michael Jackson album)|Invincible]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2002|2|8|mf=y}}\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[12-inch single|12\" single]]\n| recorded   = 2001\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = <!-- Sourced in Composition section. Do not add unsourced genres -->\n*[[Rhythm and blues]]\n*[[neo soul]]\n*[[lo-fi]]\n| length     = 4:40\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Andre Harris]], [[Marsha Ambrosius]], [[Michael Jackson]]\n| producer   = Michael Jackson, Andre Harris\n| prev_title = [[Cry (Michael Jackson song)|Cry]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[One More Chance (Michael Jackson song)|One More Chance]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|csvNBRZfFpo|\"Butterflies (Audio)\"}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Michael Jackson's Butterflies.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Butterflies'''\" is a song by American singer, songwriter, and dancer [[Michael Jackson]]. It was written and composed by [[Andre Harris]] and [[Marsha Ambrosius]], and produced by Jackson and Harris. The track appears on Jackson's tenth studio album, ''[[Invincible (Michael Jackson album)|Invincible]]'' (2001), and is Jackson's final single from a studio album. The song also appeared in \"[[The Ultimate Collection (Michael Jackson album)|The Ultimate Collection]]\" (2004). \"Butterflies\" is a [[tempo|midtempo]] ballad. The single received generally positive reviews from music critics; some music reviewers described the song as being one of the best songs on ''Invincible'' while others felt that it was a \"decent track\".\n\nThe song was only released in the United States to radio airplay. It peaked at number fourteen on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and also charting at number two and thirty-six, respectively, on alternative ''Billboard'' charts in 2001 and 2002. There was no music video released for the song.\n\n==Background and development==\n\"Butterflies\" was recorded by [[Michael Jackson]] in 2001 for his tenth studio album, ''Invincible'', which was released the same year.<ref name=\"linernotes\">''Invincible'' liner notes [[Epic Records]] (2001)</ref> The song was written by Andre Harris and Marsha Ambrosius, who is one half of the London bred [[neo-soul]] act Floetry,<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> and was produced by Jackson and Harris.<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> Jackson first met Ambrosius and Natalie Stewart, who is also a member of [[Floetry]], through John McClain, who is [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]]'s senior urban executive and Jackson's manager.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> Stewart said she was surprised that Jackson invited her and Ambrosius to a studio and asked for their input on the recording of the track.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> She recalled in an interview with [[LAUNCH Media|''LAUNCH'' magazine]], \"It was incredible because he asked, he continually asked, 'Marsh, what's the next harmony? Girls, does this sound right? What do you think? Is this what you were looking for? He was so open\".<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/>\n\nWhen Ambrosius first met Jackson, it took a few minutes to calm down.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> She recalled to the same publication Stewart was interviewed by, \"To begin with, I was kinda shook. Because you don't realize how you're going to feel until you're put in that situation. I had the tears in my eyes and got kinda nervous. But as I got into it, I realized it was work, it was a job. I had to vocally conduct a legend.\"<ref name=\"yahoomusic\"/> Harris commented on the single, \"He's showing you, I'm still the Michael Jackson that did '[[Billie Jean]]' and '[[Rock with You (Michael Jackson song)|Rock With You]]' because 'Butterflies' really falls along those lines.\"<ref name=\"theatlanitcjournal\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F0F007E21514E96&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=With a new album, a popular single, and in demand as a hot commodity on television, Michael Jackson proves he's still.... A fan favorite |publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]] |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |date=2002-01-09 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\nUnlike the previous single released from ''Invincible'', a music video was not made to promote the song.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/134224701.html?dids=134224701:134224701&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+09%2C+2002&author=CHUCK+PHILIPS&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Power%2C+Money+Behind+Jackson's+Attack+on+Sony%2C+Insiders+Say%3B+Music%3A+Some+in+the+industry+question+the+pop+singer's+motives+in+going+after+his+longtime+record+company.&pqatl=google |title=Power, Money Behind Jackson's Attack on Sony, Insiders Say; Music: Some in the industry question the pop singer's motives in going after his longtime record company. |first=Chuck |last=Phillips |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=2002-07-09 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Butterflies\" is a [[tempo|midtempo]] love ballad song with groove musical influences.<ref name=\"buffalonews\"/><ref name=\"n.s.t\"/><ref name=\"nyt\"/> Vaughn Watson of the ''[[Providence Journal]]'' noted that the track is a \"velvety old-school soul ballad\" with \"elegiac horn riffs\" and \"simple '70s-style [[David Ruffin]] soul.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Spears and Jackson: Mostly stuck in old grooves |first=Vaughn |last=Watson |publisher=[[A. H. Belo]] |work=[[Providence Journal]] |date=2001-11-11}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]], a writer for [[AllMusic]] noted that \"Butterflies\" had \"[[Burt Bacharach|Bacharach]]-styled horns.\"<ref name=\"allmusicreview\"/> Lonell Broadnax, Jr., a contributing writer to the Daily Helmsman Online felt that \"Butterflies\" is a soulful song which takes Jackson back to his \"rhythm and blues roots\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.www.dailyhelmsman.com/media/storage/paper875/news/2001/10/31/ArtsEntertainment/In.Fans.Eyes.Jackson.Still.invincible-1752586.shtml |title=In fans' eyes, Jackson still 'Invincible' |publisher=Daily Helmsman Online |date=2010-10-31 |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006045016/http://media.www.dailyhelmsman.com/media/storage/paper875/news/2001/10/31/ArtsEntertainment/In.Fans.Eyes.Jackson.Still.invincible-1752586.shtml |archivedate=2008-10-06 }}</ref> Ben Rayer of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' felt that the song had a \"oozy slow jam\".<ref name=\"tornontostar\"/>  \"Butterflies\" is written in the [[time signature]] of common time.<ref name=\"sheet\"/> Throughout the song Jackson's [[vocal range]] spans from E{{music|flat}}3 to E{{music|flat}}5.<ref name=\"sheet\"/> The track is played in the [[key (music)|key]] of A{{music|flat}} major.<ref name=\"sheet\">{{cite web |url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0041745|title=Butterflies \u2013 Michael Jackson Digital Sheet Music (Digital Download)|work=MusicNotes.com|publisher=[[Alfred Publishing|Alfred Publishing Co. Inc]]|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref> \"Butterflies\" has a moderately slowly tempo and its metronome is ninety-two [[beats per minute]].<ref name=\"sheet\"/>\n\n==Critical response==\nThe track received generally positive reviews from music critics. Ken Barnes of ''[[USA Today]]'' described the song as being a \"hopelessly sappy ballad oozing with fuzzy sentiments. I'd say it's more like caterpillars.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/96970620.html?dids=96970620:96970620&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+27%2C+2001&author=Ken+Barnes&pub=USA+TODAY&desc=Singling+out+the+year's+high%2C+low+notes&pqatl=google |first=Ken |last=Barnes |title=Singling out the year's high, low notes |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=Gannett Co. Inc |date=2001-12-21 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Frank Kogan of ''[[The Village Voice]]'', citing the lyrics, \"I would give you anything baby, just make my dreams come true/Oh baby you give me butterflies\" wrote \"so, would he give her, like, caterpillars in exchange? birds?\" and added that what grabs his attention about a song like \"Butterflies\" is not the \"melody but the weirdly ringing wrench-against-faucet clang on the backbeat.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2001-11-27/music/the-man-in-the-distance/ |title=The Man in the Distance |first=Frank |last=Kogan |work=[[The Village Voice]] |publisher=[[Village Voice Media]] |date=2001-11-27 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Christie Leo of the ''[[New Straits Times]]'' gave the track a more positive review, calling the song a \"luxuriant\" ballad.<ref name=\"n.s.t\">{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-82629981.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104020259/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-82629981.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-11-04 |title=Article: Compelling Tori |first=Christie |last=Leo |publisher=[[Media Prima]] |work=[[New Straits Times]] |date=2001-12-02 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Pop music critic [[Robert Hilburn]], writing for the ''Los Angeles Times'', described \"Butterflies\", and another song from ''Invincible'' (\"[[Speechless (Michael Jackson song)|Speechless]]\"), as being \"as woefully generic as their titles\".<ref name=\"Michael Jackson's 'Invincible'\">{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-archive-invincible-review-oct28,0,1825017.story|title=Michael Jackson's 'Invincible' |last=Hilburn |first=Robert |date=2001-10-28 |publisher=Tribune Company |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> A journalist of the same publication felt that track was about romantic \"jitters\".<ref name=\"Michael Jackson's 'Invincible2'\">{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/86729836.html?dids=86729836:86729836&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+28%2C+2001&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Pop+Music%3B+Record+Rack%3B+All+the+King's+Men+Can't+Help&pqatl=google |title=Pop Music; Record Rack; All the King's Men Can't Help|date=2001-10-28 |publisher=Tribune Company |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\nDarryl Frierson of ''University Wire'' felt that songs like \"Butterflies\" can set the \"mood for any romantic interlude\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-47950587.html |title=Article: CD REVIEW: New album proves Michael Jackson is 'invincible' |first=Darryl |last=Frierson |publisher=University Wire |date=2001-11-05 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Joel Rubinoff of ''The Record'' said that \"Butterflies\" was one of the \"only good songs\" from ''Invincible'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/432937431.html?dids=432937431:432937431&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+03%2C+2001&author=Joel+Rubinoff&pub=The+Record&desc=What+has+Michael+Jackson+done+to+deserve+this%3F&pqatl=google |title=What has Michael Jackson done to deserve this? |first=Joel |last=Rubinoff |publisher=The Record |date=2001-11-03 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> while a writer for ''[[The Atlanta Journal]]'' cited the song as being a \"decent track\".<ref>{{cite news |title=He's been 'Dangerous', 'Bad,' now -- ho-hum -- 'Invincible'  |publisher=Cox Enterprises |work=[[The Atlanta Journal]] |date=2001-10-31}}</ref>\n\nA writer for ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' viewed \"Butterflies\" as being \"laid-back\".<ref name=\"theatlanitcjournal\"/> Mark Anthony Neal of ''[[PopMatters]]'' wrote in his music review for Jackson's 2002 album, entitled ''Love Songs'', that in song's such as \"Butterflies\", it shows the \"essence\" of Jackson's \"genius has been in the boy's uncanny ability to perform, even the mundane, outside of the box.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/j/jacksonmichael-love.shtml |title=Michael Jackson: Love Songs  |first=Mark Anthony |last=Neal |work=[[PopMatters]] |publisher=PopMatters Media, Inc |date=2002-01-15 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Elliot Sylvester of ''[[The Independent]]'' felt that ballads on ''Invincible'' such as \"Speechless and \"Butterflies\" are \"almost to a formulaic fault.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Invincible shows that Jackson is not |first=Elliot |last=Sylvester |publisher=[[Alexander Lebedev]] |work=[[The Independent]] |date=2002-01-14}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' rock music critic Greg Kot said that Jackson is not \"convincing as the vulnerable ladies' man on drippy ballads\" such as \"Butterflies\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/86764359.html?dids=86764359:86764359&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+29%2C+2001&author=Greg+Kot%2C+Tribune+rock+critic&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Neither+off-the-wall+nor+off-the-charts+%3B+Michael+Jackson's+%60Invincible'+a+big+disappointment&pqatl=google |title=Neither off-the-wall nor off-the-charts ; Michael Jackson's `Invincible' a big disappointment |first=Greg |last=Kot |work=Chicago Tribune |publisher=Tribune Company |date=2001-10-29 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Stephen Thomas Erlewine, a writer for Allmusic, commented that ''Invincible'' was \"highlighted\" by \"lovely ballads\" such as \"Break of Dawn\" and \"Butterflies\".<ref name=\"allmusicreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=A0dq5g4hptv8z |title=allmusic ((( Invincible &gt; Overview ))) |first=Stephen Thomas |last=Erlewine |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012150712/http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=A0dq5g4hptv8z |archivedate=October 12, 2007 }}</ref> David Browne of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote in his review for ''Invincible'' that, \"The ballads are a squishy bunch with glaringly banal lyrics, pleasantries like 'Butterflies' and 'Break of Dawn' that could emanate from just about\" anyone.<ref name=\"e.w.review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,253595,00.html |title=Invincible (2001) |author=David Browne |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=Time Warner Inc |date=2001-11-09 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> A journalist for ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' called the track \"gorgeous\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF9D51191826730&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=King of Pop is back, with slick, soulless 'Invincible' |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=2001-11-04 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> and Bomani Jones of [[Salon.com]] called \"Butterflies\" a \"sparkling\" track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/music/feature/2002/06/26/jacko |title=Who's bad? |work=[[Salon.com]] |publisher=Salon Media Group, Inc |first=Bomani |last=Jones |date=2002-06-26 |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624085257/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/music/feature/2002/06/26/jacko |archivedate=2010-06-24 }}</ref> Ben Rayer of the ''Toronto Star'' wrote that Jackson \"fares best\" on \"Butterflies\".<ref name=\"tornontostar\">{{cite news |title=Invincible incredibly insipid ; New album is not the come-back Jackson has been hoping for |first=Ben |last=Rayner |publisher=[[Torstar]] |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2001-10-31}}</ref>\n\nCatherine Halaby of the ''[[Yale Daily News]]'' said that songs on the album like \"Heaven Can Wait\", \"Butterflies\", and \"You Are My Life\" \"fulfill the quota for sugary ballads\".<ref name=\"yalesnews\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/scene/music/2001/11/02/jacko-exposes-mortality-in-invincible/ |title=Jacko exposes mortality in Invincible |first=Catherine |last=Halaby |publisher=The Yale Daily News Publishing Company |work=[[Yale Daily News]] |date=2001-11-02 |accessdate=2010-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916102527/http://www.yaledailynews.com/news/2001/nov/02/jacko-exposes-mortality-in-invincible/ |archivedate=2012-09-16 }}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]], writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', said that tracks on ''Invincible'' like \"Butterflies\"' and \"Don't Walk Away\" are \"melting love ballads\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/28/arts/music-to-regain-glory-the-new-michael-imitates-the-old.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 |first=Jon |last=Pareles |authorlink=Jon Pareles|title=Music; To Regain Glory, The New Michael Imitates the Old (Page 2) |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[New York Times Company]] |date=2001-10-28 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Pareles noted in his review for the album that songs on it are recurring themes present on Jackson's albums, such as love ballads, as well as tracks pertaining to making the world a better place.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Tim Perzyk of the ''[[Duke Chronicle]]'' wrote, \"By the time 'Butterflies' spins on track seven, it's unclear why Michael didn't record a collaborative boxed set with [[Mariah Carey]], whose '[[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]],' '[[Breakdown (Mariah Carey song)|Breakdown]]' and '[[Butterfly (Mariah Carey song)|Butterfly]]' would fit quite nicely\" into Jackson's ''Invincible'' album.<ref name=\"Jackson sucks\">{{cite web |url=http://dukechronicle.com/article/jackson-sucks|title=Jackson sucks |last=Perzyk |first=Tim |date=2001-11-02 |publisher=DSPC |work=[[Duke Chronicle]] |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Pop music critic Craid Seymour of the ''[[Buffalo News]]'' wrote that \"another winning tune\" on the album is the \"dreamy 'Butterflies,' which flows along at a groovy midtempo pace.\"<ref name=\"buffalonews\">{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF6A5BCB107E9D8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=SAME OLD JACKO |first=Craig |last=Seymour |publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]] |work=[[Buffalo News]] |date=2001-10-26 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Kevin C. Johnson of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' described \"Butterflies\" as being about the \"feeling that special someone gives him.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF8ACBD77152066&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=JACKSON'S \"INVINCIBLE\" ISN'T \"BAD, \"JUST \"OLD\" |first=Kevin C. |last=Johnson |publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]] |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |date=2001-11-02 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> Music critics writing for the ''[[South Florida Sun Sentinel]]'' said that the track shows the \"shy, loving, gentle side\" of Jackson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/access/93070637.html?dids=93070637:93070637&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+30%2C+2001&author=Dwight+Roache+Stoneman+Douglas+High+By+Megan+Leap+Spanish+River+High+By+Greg+Overzat+Stoneman+Douglas+High&pub=South+Florida+Sun+-+Sentinel&desc=THE+JACKSON+LEGEND&pqatl=google |title=THE JACKSON LEGEND |publisher=Tribune Company |work=[[South Florida Sun Sentinel]] |date=2001-11-30 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Butterflies\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in early November 2001, at number sixty.<ref name=\"yahoomusic\">{{cite web |url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/michael-jackson/news/artist-name-michael-jackson-id-1013025-songwriter-gets-the-butterflies--12063973 |title=Songwriter Gets The 'Butterflies' |first=Billy |last=Johnson Jr. |work=Yahoo Music |publisher=Yahoo Inc |date=2001-11-15 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> The single eventually peaked at number fourteen on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 the week ending January 26, 2002. The track also charted within the top ten, peaking at number two, on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart on January 26, 2002;<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/> the song was held from the top position from [[Ja Rule]] and [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]]'s \"[[Always on Time]]\" 2001 single.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2002-01-26/r-b-hip-hop-songs |title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs: Week of January 26, 2002 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]] |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> In 2002, \"Butterflies\" also peaked at number thirty-six on the ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Charts|Top 40 Mainstream]] chart.<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/> The track, which was released as a promotional single internationally, did not chart on any music charts outside of the United States.<ref name=\"lescharts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Butterflies&cat=s |title=MICHAEL JACKSON - BUTTERFLIES (CHANSON) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref> The song was Jackson's last hit single in the United States in the final years of his career.\n\n==Track listings==\n;Promo CD single (Epic ESK 54863)<ref name=\"lescharts\"/>\n# \"Butterflies\" (album version) \u2013 4:40\n\n;Michael Jackson - Butterflies (Track Masters Remix)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Michael-Jackson-Butterflies-Track-Masters-Remix/release/459620 |title=Michael Jackson - Butterflies (Track Masters Remix) |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=2001-05-10}}</ref>\n*A1. \"Butterflies\" (Master Mix) (featuring Eve) \u2013 3:47\n*A2. \"Butterflies\" (Michael a cappella) \u2013 2:13\n*B1. \"Butterflies\" (Eve a cappella) (featuring Eve) \u2013 3:47\n*B2. \"Butterflies\" (Master Mix Instrumental) \u2013 3:47\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n* Written and composed by Andre Harris, Michael Jackson and Marsha Ambrosius\n* Produced by Michael Jackson and Andre Harris\n* [[Lead vocalist|Lead vocal]] by Michael Jackson\n* Background vocals by Michael Jackson and Marsha Ambrosius\n* All musical instruments performed by Andre Harris\n* [[French horn|Horns]] by Norman Jeff Bradshaw and Matt Cappy\n* Recorded by Andre Harris and Bruce Swedien\n* Assistant engineering by Vidal Davis\n* Mixed by Bruce Rammkisoon\n\nSource:<ref>Liner notes of ''Invincible'' (2001).</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2002)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]]<ref name=\"billboard singles\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Charts|Top 40 Mainstream]]<ref name=\"billboard singles\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r553140|pure_url=yes}} |title=allmusic ((( Invincible > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles ))) |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref>\n|align=center|36\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2002)\n!Position\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billboardtop100of.com/2002-2/|title=Billboard Top 100 \u2013 2002|website=Billboardtop100of.com|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|64\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.discogs.com/Michael-Jackson-Butterflies/release/1994507 \"Butterflies\"] at [[Discogs]]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|michael-jackson|butterflies}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Michael Jackson songs}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butterflies (Michael Jackson Song)}}\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:2002 singles]]\n[[Category:Michael Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n[[Category:Contemporary R&B ballads]]\n[[Category:Soul ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Andre Harris]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Marsha Ambrosius]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Michael Jackson]]\n", "name_user": "Rmcrae2015", "label": "safe", "comment": "Song is Contemporary R&B", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butterflies_(Michael_Jackson_song)"}
{"title_page": "Niue Rugby Football Union", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=August 2015}}\n[[File:Rugbyniue.png|right|thumb|Niue Rugby Logo]]\n'''Niue Rugby Football Union''' is the governing body for [[rugby union]] in [[Niue]]. It was founded in 1952,<ref name = rfh-2014/> and became affiliated to the [[World Rugby]] (formerly the IRB) in 1999.\n\nThe Niue Rugby Football Union is a member of the [[Federation of Oceania Rugby Unions]] (FORU),<ref name = foru-2014/><ref name = foru-mission/> and was also a member of the former [[Pacific Islands Rugby Alliance]] and was eligible to supply players to the [[Pacific Islanders rugby union team|Pacific Islanders team]].\n\n==Rugby union in Niue==\n{{Sport overview\n| country         = Niue\n| sport           = rugby union\n| image           = \n| imagesize       = 300px\n| caption         = \n| union           = Niue Rugby Football Union\n| nickname        = \n| first           = Turn of 20th century\n| registered      = 290\n| clubs           = 7\n| match           = \n| nationa_list    = [[Rugby World Cup]]<br/>[[Rugby World Cup Sevens]]<br/>[[IRB Sevens World Series]]\n| club_list       = \n| countryflag     = Niue\n}}\n[[File:Niuean haka.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Niue sevens team performing a [[haka]].]]\n[[Rugby union]] is the most popular sport in [[Niue]].<ref>{{cite book |title=South Pacific and Micronesia |publisher=[[Lonely Planet]] |first= |last= |year=2006 |edition= |page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/53 53] |isbn=1-74104-304-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/53 }}</ref> It is a tier-three rugby union playing nation.\n\n==National team==\nThe [[Niue national rugby union team]] first started playing in 1983. They have yet to qualify for the [[Rugby World Cup]].\n\nNiue won the current [[FORU Oceania Cup]] in 2008, defeating [[New Caledonia national rugby union team|New Caledonia]] 27\u20135 in the final on 1 September 2008.<ref>[http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/news/stories/200809/s2352343.htm?tab=sport \"Niue take Oceania Cup rugby union final\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916221921/http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/news/stories/200809/s2352343.htm?tab=sport |date=16 September 2008 }}, ABC Radio Australia, 1 September 2008</ref>\n\n==History==\nTeams from Niue have competed in the [[Commonwealth Games]].\n\nWhen Niue competed in the 2001 Wellington 7s, they took a completely local-based squad, and though they scored tries against [[England national rugby union team|England]] and [[Canada national rugby union team|Canada]], they were crushed in most games. Infamously, they surprised everyone by beating Japan 31\u201319 in 2002.\n\nThe New Zealand player [[Frank Bunce]] is the great nephew of Sir [[Robert Rex]], the former Premier of [[Niue]].<ref>{{cite book |title=South Pacific and Micronesia |publisher=[[Lonely Planet]] |first= |last= |year=2006 |edition= |page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/358 358] |isbn=1-74104-304-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/358 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Niue national rugby union team]]\n*[[Niue national rugby sevens team]]\n*[[Niue Island Sports Association]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist<!--|colwidth=25em-->|refs=\n<ref name = foru-mission>{{cite web \n |year=2013 \n |title= FORU's Mission\n |website= oceaniarugby.com\n |accessdate= 11 November 2013\n |url= http://www.oceaniarugby.com/home.html\n |url-status= live\n |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131111013512/http://www.oceaniarugby.com/home.html\n |archivedate= 11 November 2013}}\n</ref>\n<ref name = rfh-2014>{{cite web \n |date= 2014\n |title= National Unions List\n |publisher= Rugby Football History\n |accessdate= 2 February 2015\n |url=  http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/National_Unions_List.htm\n |url-status= live\n |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141009222631/http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/National_Unions_List.htm\n |archivedate= 9 October 2014}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name = foru-2014>{{cite web \n |date= 2015\n |title= Niue Rugby Union\n |publisher= FORU\n |accessdate= 2 February 2015\n |url= http://www.oceaniarugby.com/member_unions/foru_member_union_niue.html\n |url-status= live\n |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140518064556/http://oceaniarugby.com/member_unions/foru_member_union_niue.html\n |archivedate= 18 May 2014}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110925013354/http://www.irb.com/unions/union=11000060/index.html IRB Niue page]\n<!-- * [ official union page] -->\n* [http://www.oceaniarugby.com/member_unions/foru_member_union_niue.html Federation of Oceania Rugby Unions, Niue page]\n* [http://www.pacificnationsrugby.com/teams-Niue.aspx Oceania Nations, Niue]\n\n{{Rugby union in Niue}}\n{{Rugby union in}}\n{{Women's Rugby World Cup Unions}}\n{{Oceania in topic|Rugby union in}}\n{{Rugby union outside WC}}\n\n[[Category:Rugby union in Niue]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Niue]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in Niue]]\n[[Category:Rugby union governing bodies in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1952]]\n\n\n{{Niue-stub}}\n{{Rugbyunion-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2015}}\n[[File:Rugbyniue.png|right|thumb|Niue Rugby Logo]]\n'''Niue Rugby Football Union''' is the governing body for [[rugby union]] in [[Niue]]. It was founded in 1952,<ref name = rfh-2014/> and became affiliated to the [[World Rugby]] (formerly the IRB) in 1999.\n\nThe Niue Rugby Football Union is a member of the [[Federation of Oceania Rugby Unions]] (FORU),<ref name = foru-2014/><ref name = foru-mission/> and was also a member of the former [[Pacific Islands Rugby Alliance]] and was eligible to supply players to the [[Pacific Islanders rugby union team|Pacific Islanders team]].\n\n==Rugby union in Niue==\n{{Sport overview\n| country         = Niue\n| sport           = rugby union\n| image           = \n| imagesize       = 300px\n| caption         = \n| union           = Niue Rugby Football Union\n| nickname        = \n| first           = Turn of 20th century\n| registered      = 290\n| clubs           = 7\n| match           = \n| nationa_list    = [[Rugby World Cup]]<br/>[[Rugby World Cup Sevens]]<br/>[[IRB Sevens World Series]]\n| club_list       = \n| countryflag     = Niue\n}}\n[[File:Niuean haka.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Niue sevens team performing a [[haka]].]]\n[[Rugby union]] is the most popular sport in [[Niue]].<ref>{{cite book |title=South Pacific and Micronesia |publisher=[[Lonely Planet]] |first= |last= |year=2006 |edition= |page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/53 53] |isbn=1-74104-304-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/53 }}</ref> It is a tier-three rugby union playing nation.\n\n==National team==\nThe [[Niue national rugby union team]] first started playing in 1983. They have yet to qualify for the [[Rugby World Cup]].\n\nNiue won the current [[FORU Oceania Cup]] in 2008, defeating [[New Caledonia national rugby union team|New Caledonia]] 27-5 in the final on 1 September 2008.<ref>[http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/news/stories/200809/s2352343.htm?tab=sport \"Niue take Oceania Cup rugby union final\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916221921/http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/news/stories/200809/s2352343.htm?tab=sport |date=16 September 2008 }}, ABC Radio Australia, 1 September 2008</ref>\n\n==History==\nTeams from Niue have competed in the [[Commonwealth Games]].\n\nWhen Niue competed in the 2001 Wellington 7s, they took a completely local-based squad, and though they scored tries against [[England national rugby union team|England]] and [[Canada national rugby union team|Canada]], they were crushed in most games. Infamously, they surprised everyone by beating Japan 31-19 in 2002.\n\nThe New Zealand player [[Frank Bunce]] is the great nephew of Sir [[Robert Rex]], the former Premier of [[Niue]].<ref>{{cite book |title=South Pacific and Micronesia |publisher=[[Lonely Planet]] |first= |last= |year=2006 |edition= |page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/358 358] |isbn=1-74104-304-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetsout00geer/page/358 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Niue national rugby union team]]\n*[[Niue national rugby sevens team]]\n*[[Niue Island Sports Association]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist<!--|colwidth=25em-->|refs=\n<ref name = foru-mission>{{cite web \n |year=2013 \n |title= FORU's Mission\n |website= oceaniarugby.com\n |accessdate= 11 November 2013\n |url= http://www.oceaniarugby.com/home.html\n |url-status= live\n |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131111013512/http://www.oceaniarugby.com/home.html\n |archivedate= 11 November 2013}}\n</ref>\n<ref name = rfh-2014>{{cite web \n |date= 2014\n |title= National Unions List\n |publisher= Rugby Football History\n |accessdate= 2 February 2015\n |url=  http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/National_Unions_List.htm\n |url-status= live\n |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141009222631/http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/National_Unions_List.htm\n |archivedate= 9 October 2014}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name = foru-2014>{{cite web \n |date= 2015\n |title= Niue Rugby Union\n |publisher= FORU\n |accessdate= 2 February 2015\n |url= http://www.oceaniarugby.com/member_unions/foru_member_union_niue.html\n |url-status= live\n |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140518064556/http://oceaniarugby.com/member_unions/foru_member_union_niue.html\n |archivedate= 18 May 2014}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110925013354/http://www.irb.com/unions/union=11000060/index.html IRB Niue page]\n<!-- * [ official union page] -->\n* [http://www.oceaniarugby.com/member_unions/foru_member_union_niue.html Federation of Oceania Rugby Unions, Niue page]\n* [http://www.pacificnationsrugby.com/teams-Niue.aspx Oceania Nations, Niue]\n\n{{Rugby union in Niue}}\n{{Rugby 